## Fix MCP server pointing at the wrong OntoBricks app

Context: deployed MCP server's ``list_domains`` tool was returning
"No domains found in the registry." even though the
``ontobricks-020`` app exposes seven MCP-enabled domains via
``/api/v1/domains``.

Investigation (verified live against the deployed apps):

1. The MCP server's ``list_domains`` tool forwards the bound
   Volume coordinates (``REGISTRY_VOLUME_PATH``) as
   ``registry_catalog`` / ``registry_schema`` / ``registry_volume``
   query params on every ``/api/v1/...`` call. Those overrides win
   inside ``DigitalTwin.resolve_registry``, re-targeting the main
   app at the catalog/schema/volume the MCP is bound to.
2. The MCP's ``app.yaml`` had ``ONTOBRICKS_URL`` pointing at the
   *legacy* ``ontobricks-…`` deployment, whose session-default
   registry resolves to ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_deployed.registry``.
   The current canonical app is ``ontobricks-020-…``, bound to
   ``benoit_cayla.ontobricks_020.registry``.
3. Forwarding ``registry_schema=ontobricks_020`` to the legacy app
   silently re-pointed it at a Volume that holds two domain folders
   (``contactcenter``, ``cust360auto``) of which neither has any
   ``mcp_enabled`` version → empty list → the MCP message above.
4. Pointing the MCP at ``ontobricks-020-…`` makes the override
   match the main app's session default, so the call returns the
   seven MCP-enabled domains as expected.

Changes:

1. src/mcp-server/app.yaml
   Updated ``ONTOBRICKS_URL`` from
   ``https://ontobricks-2508734981122804.aws.databricksapps.com``
   to
   ``https://ontobricks-020-2508734981122804.aws.databricksapps.com``
   so the MCP companion talks to the same app whose UC Volume
   binding it shares. Added an inline note explaining that any
   future drift between this URL and the bound Volume will
   silently re-route the main app at the wrong registry.

Modified files:
- src/mcp-server/app.yaml

Deploy:
- ``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase`` (no source change
  on the main app; only the MCP picks up the new env var)
- ``databricks bundle run mcp_ontobricks_app -t dev-lakebase`` to
  restart the MCP container so the new ``ONTOBRICKS_URL`` is
  loaded into the process environment.

Verification (live against the deployed apps):
- MCP ``/`` health reports
  ``ontobricks_url: https://ontobricks-020-…databricksapps.com``
  and ``registry: /Volumes/benoit_cayla/ontobricks_020/registry``.
- Reproducing the MCP's exact GET against the new URL with the
  override params returns ``success: true`` with seven domains
  (``bookstore``, ``contactcenter``, ``cust360auto``,
  ``monorganisation``, ``predictivemaintenance``, ``suplychain``,
  ``transport``).

Tests: ``uv run pytest -q`` → 1893 passed in 59.08s.

Follow-up (deferred, recommended):
- Make the MCP's ``_registry_params()`` opt-in or treat
  ``REGISTRY_VOLUME_PATH`` as a *fallback* — call the main app's
  ``/api/v1/digitaltwin/registry`` first and only override when
  that endpoint reports the registry is unconfigured. Today any
  binding drift between the two apps silently re-routes the main
  app to a possibly empty Volume instead of failing loud.

----------------------------------------------------------------
Title: MCP server — observable startup + per-request HTTP logging

Context: After the URL/permission fix above, a follow-up incident
(see "Lakebase rebind incident" below) showed the MCP was returning
opaque error strings to the LLM ("502 Bad Gateway", "401
Unauthorized") with no way to see, inside the deployed Apps log
stream, *what URL it called*, *with which params*, *and what came
back*. The MCP's own ``logger.info(...)`` calls in
``server/app.py`` were dropped because no logging configuration was
applied at startup — uvicorn only configures its access/error
loggers, leaving the project's loggers at WARNING.

Changes:
1. ``src/mcp-server/server/main.py`` — add ``_configure_logging()``
   helper (called from ``main()`` before ``uvicorn.run``) that
   installs a single stream handler at the level requested by
   ``MCP_LOG_LEVEL`` (default ``INFO``). Sets ``logging.getLogger
   ("server").setLevel(level)`` so every module under
   ``server.*`` is captured, and pins ``httpx`` to ``WARNING`` to
   avoid noisy per-request DEBUG lines from the underlying client.
2. ``src/mcp-server/server/app.py`` — ``_get(client, path, params)``
   now logs ``GET <full_url> params=<params>`` *before* the call,
   the response status *after*, and on 4xx/5xx adds a 500-char body
   excerpt at ``WARNING``. This is what surfaced the
   ``infrastructure / permission denied for schema
   ontobricks_registry`` line during the Lakebase rebind incident
   below — without it, the deployed app would just have surfaced
   ``HTTPStatusError`` strings.
3. ``src/mcp-server/server/app.py`` — ``_get_auth_headers`` now
   logs (at DEBUG) whether the M2M OAuth token came from cache and
   how old the cached token is, so ``401`` symptoms can be
   bisected against token freshness without redeploying.
4. ``src/mcp-server/server/app.py`` — ``create_mcp_server`` now
   emits a one-line "Env snapshot" at startup capturing
   ``REGISTRY_VOLUME_PATH``, ``REGISTRY_CATALOG/SCHEMA/VOLUME``,
   ``DATABRICKS_HOST``, presence of ``DATABRICKS_CLIENT_ID/SECRET``
   (boolean only — never the secret value), and
   ``DATABRICKS_SQL_WAREHOUSE_ID``. With this, the very first log
   line of every Apps deploy tells you exactly which main app the
   MCP is bound to and which registry override it will forward.
5. ``src/mcp-server/server/app.py`` — ``list_domains`` now logs
   ``Tool list_domains called`` on entry and the resolved
   ``base_url + path + override_params`` immediately before the
   HTTP call, so every tool invocation has a clean audit trail in
   the log stream.

Modified files:
- src/mcp-server/server/main.py
- src/mcp-server/server/app.py

Deploy:
- ``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase
   --var=registry_schema=ontobricks_020`` (the bundle's default
  ``ontobricks_030`` schema does not exist in this workspace —
  override at the CLI rather than mutate ``databricks.yml`` so the
  user's source-controlled defaults are preserved).
- ``databricks bundle run mcp_ontobricks_app -t dev-lakebase
   --var=registry_schema=ontobricks_020`` to restart the MCP
  container with the new logging config in place.

Verification:
- New first log line on the MCP after restart reads:
  ``Env snapshot — REGISTRY_VOLUME_PATH='…' REGISTRY_CATALOG=''
   REGISTRY_SCHEMA='' REGISTRY_VOLUME='' DATABRICKS_HOST='…'
   DATABRICKS_CLIENT_ID=set DATABRICKS_CLIENT_SECRET=set
   DATABRICKS_SQL_WAREHOUSE_ID='…'``
- Calling ``tools/call list_domains`` against the deployed MCP
  via curl returns the seven expected domains (``bookstore`` …
  ``transport``) and emits ``Tool list_domains called`` →
  ``GET https://ontobricks-020-…/api/v1/domains params={…}`` →
  ``→ 200`` in the Apps log stream.

Tests: ``uv run pytest -q`` → 1893 passed in 65.56s.

