Title: Lakebase rebind incident — ``ontobricks-020`` postgres
       binding accidentally migrated v030 → production restore

Context: While redeploying the MCP for the URL fix above, the
``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase`` command was run with
the bundle's default ``lakebase_branch: v030``. That default
silently *rewrote* the ``ontobricks-020`` ``postgres:`` resource
binding from ``projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production/...`` to
``projects/ontobricks-app/branches/v030/...``. The running app
process kept its old PG env vars (process restart didn't happen
yet) but token minting now keys off the new resource binding, so
``/api/v1/domains`` started returning HTTP 502 with
``Lakebase connection failed: password authentication failed for
user '<sp-client-id>'``. (This was only visible *because* of the
new MCP request/response logging from the change above, otherwise
the user would just have seen the bare ``502 Bad Gateway`` from
the LLM tool layer.) Bisecting the bundle's two Lakebase branches
with ``databricks postgres list-endpoints`` confirmed that
``v030`` resolves to ``ep-floral-meadow-d1y55ilx`` (a brand-new,
empty endpoint created by my own deploy) while ``production``
resolves to ``ep-young-bread-d1f2p5nq`` (where the real registry
data lives).

Fix:
1. Re-deployed the bundle with ``--var=lakebase_branch=production
   --var=registry_schema=ontobricks_020`` to revert the
   ``ontobricks-020`` postgres binding to ``branches/production``.
   Did **not** edit ``databricks.yml`` — the bundle's defaults are
   the user's source of truth and the override stays at the CLI.
2. Restarted ``ontobricks-020`` via
   ``databricks bundle run ontobricks_dev_app -t dev-lakebase
   --var=lakebase_branch=production --var=registry_schema=
   ontobricks_020`` so the process picks up the restored
   ``PGHOST = ep-young-bread-d1f2p5nq`` env var.
3. Restarted ``mcp-ontobricks`` with the same ``--var`` overrides
   for parity (it does not depend on the binding directly but its
   resource block is declared symmetrically and we wanted the
   bundle state and the running state to match).
4. ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`` could not be reused as-
   is here: it walks ``projects/<inst>/branches`` in API order and
   takes the *first* endpoint, which is ``v030`` for this
   instance. We instead executed the same GRANT block manually
   against the ``production`` endpoint
   (``ep-young-bread-d1f2p5nq``):

   ::

      ENDPOINT_PATH=projects/ontobricks-app/branches/production/endpoints/primary
      PGPASSWORD=$(databricks api post /api/2.0/postgres/credentials \\
        --json "{\\"endpoint\\":\\"$ENDPOINT_PATH\\"}" \\
        | python3 -c 'import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)[\"token\"])')
      psql "host=ep-young-bread-d1f2p5nq.database.us-west-2.cloud.databricks.com \\
            port=5432 user=$PGUSER dbname=ontobricks_registry sslmode=require" <<SQL
      GRANT USAGE, CREATE ON SCHEMA "ontobricks_registry" TO "<sp-client-id>";
      GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE
        ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA "ontobricks_registry" TO "<sp-client-id>";
      GRANT USAGE, SELECT, UPDATE
        ON ALL SEQUENCES IN SCHEMA "ontobricks_registry" TO "<sp-client-id>";
      ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES IN SCHEMA "ontobricks_registry"
        GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON TABLES TO "<sp-client-id>";
      ALTER DEFAULT PRIVILEGES IN SCHEMA "ontobricks_registry"
        GRANT USAGE, SELECT, UPDATE ON SEQUENCES TO "<sp-client-id>";
      SQL

   This was repeated for both service principals
   ``cf03a7b1-4c1e-4904-b333-ebcfbc425116`` (``ontobricks-020``)
   and ``a99b4987-2c5a-48b5-a578-c4a39a0feb0d`` (``mcp-ontobricks``).

Modified files: none — pure infrastructure restore. No source
files were touched as part of this restore step.

Verification:
- ``GET /api/v1/domains`` directly against the main app returns
  the 7 expected domains (no ``error: infrastructure``).
- Same call with the MCP's full override
  ``?registry_catalog=benoit_cayla&registry_schema=ontobricks_020
   &registry_volume=registry`` returns the same 7 domains, proving
  the override path is healthy.
- End-to-end ``tools/call list_domains`` via the deployed MCP
  returns the 7-domain table to the LLM client.

Tests: ``uv run pytest -q`` → 1893 passed in 65.56s.

Follow-up (deferred, recommended):
- ``scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh`` should accept a
  ``-b/--branch`` flag (or grant on *all* endpoints across *all*
  branches under the project) instead of taking the first branch
  the API returns. Today, when the project has more than one
  branch (``v030``, ``production``), the script silently grants
  on the wrong endpoint and the operator only finds out when the
  app starts hitting ``permission denied for schema …``.
- The bundle's ``lakebase_branch`` default in ``databricks.yml``
  currently says ``v030`` while the live binding for
  ``ontobricks-020`` is ``production``. Any future
  ``databricks bundle deploy -t dev-lakebase`` without
  ``--var=lakebase_branch=production`` will silently rebind the
  app again. Either align the default to ``production`` or split
  the dev-lakebase target so the var has a less surprising
  fallback.
